headline.main: Progress of the Moral War in Philadelphia.

docs.lead_paragraph: From the Philadelphia North American. Blackberry-alley, or Daponesau-street, and its interesting Courts, have long been held by the community as the center of a moral pestilence. The inhabitants of the dwellings on Walnut, Locust, Eighth and Ninth-streets, have made constant complaint of being annoyed by the swarms of abandoned women and vicious young men, who resort to this place, and shock the ears of respectable persons by the free use of the vilest language.

headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; The FAll Campaign--The Whig Joint Executive Committee. CITY POLITICS. The Haskin Investigation. Another Murder. Reunion of the Independence Guard--A New Feature. MILITARY. Court of General Sessions. Suicide by Hanging. Area Accident. Stabbing. New-York Horticultural Society--The Agricultural Show. The Common Council-- Street Assault

docs.lead_paragraph: An important meeting of the Whig Joint Executive Committee was held last evening at the Broadway House. The proceedings were of considerable interest. The attendance was large. General WM. HALL, the Chairman, was present, and in the absence of Mr. CHARLES G. DEAN, the regular Secretary, G. G. BUTLER, Esq., was chosen to act pro tem.

Bloody Assaults. New Catholic Church--Ceremony of Laying the Corner-Stone. Another Seizure. City Mortality. The City Legislature. Society of Liberals. Fatal Accidents.

docs.lead_paragraph: Another disgraceful Sabbath disturbance occurred in our City yesterday, consequent upon the excitement created by street-preaching. As usual, a crowd of persons assembled in front of the City Hall at 3 o'clock P M., embracing different grades of society and natives and foreign. docs.lead_paragraph: Williamsburg Whig Primary Meetings. The Whig Primary Meetings, for the purpose of electing members to the Whig General Committee for the city of Brooklyn, as consolidated, were held last evening, with the following result: First Word--Henry E. Ripley, Hiram P. Hardcastle, R. H. Huntley, Chas. G. Edwards, J. W. E. Smith.
